Example

Find the domain and range of the functions \(f(x) = \sin(1/x)\) and \(g(x) = \sqrt{x-1}\). (We will examine such functions in more detail in week 5).

Solution

Here is a graph of the function \(f\):


The function \(f\) is defined for all values except \(x = 0\), since we cannot divide by \(0\). (This is not obvious on the graph.)  So the domain is the set of values \(-\infty < x < 0, 0 < x < \infty\).  As \(x\) varies in this set, \(1/x\) takes all values except \(0\), so certainly all values in the range of \(\sin\) are taken except possibly \(0=\sin(0)\).  However, \(\sin(0) = \sin(\pi)\), so \(f(1/\pi) = \sin(1/(1/\pi)) = \sin(\pi)= 0\).  Therefore \(f\) takes all values in the range of \(\sin\), i.e. the range of \(f\) is the set of values \(-1 \leq y \leq 1\).

Here is a graph of the function \(g\):


The function \(g\) is only defined for values of \(x\) such that \(x-1 \geq 0\), so its domain is the set of values \(x \geq 1\).  Its range is the set of values \(0 \leq y < \infty\).
